-- Day 1: Born of a Virgin
UPDATE public.reading_plan_days 
SET context = 'Around 700 years before Jesus was born, the prophet Isaiah delivered a remarkable message to King Ahaz of Judah. The kingdom was under threat, and God offered Ahaz a sign—any sign he wanted. When Ahaz refused (falsely claiming piety), Isaiah declared that God would give a sign anyway: "The virgin will conceive and give birth to a son, and will call him Immanuel."

The Hebrew word used here is "almah," which means a young woman of marriageable age. While some argue this could simply mean "young woman," the Greek translation of the Old Testament (the Septuagint), made 200 years before Christ, translated it as "parthenos"—which unambiguously means "virgin."

Matthew, writing under the inspiration of the Holy Spirit, sees this prophecy fulfilled in Mary''s miraculous conception. The angel tells Joseph not to be afraid to take Mary as his wife because "what is conceived in her is from the Holy Spirit."

Why does the virgin birth matter? It establishes that Jesus is both fully human (born of a woman) and fully divine (conceived by the Holy Spirit). He didn''t inherit a sin nature from a human father, making Him the perfect, sinless sacrifice. The name "Immanuel" means "God with us"—and in Jesus, God literally came to dwell among humanity.

This is just the first of over 300 Old Testament prophecies that Jesus fulfilled—prophecies written centuries before His birth, copied and preserved by Jewish scribes who had no interest in supporting Christian claims.'
WHERE plan_id = (SELECT id FROM public.reading_plans WHERE slug = 'messianic-prophecies-fulfilled') 
