-- Day 2: Born in Bethlehem
UPDATE public.reading_plan_days 
SET context = 'The prophet Micah, writing around 700 BC, pinpointed the exact town where the Messiah would be born: Bethlehem Ephrathah. This wasn''t Jerusalem, the capital and religious center. It wasn''t a major city at all. Bethlehem was a small, insignificant village—yet Micah declared that from this tiny place would come "one who will be ruler over Israel, whose origins are from of old, from ancient times."

That last phrase is stunning. The ruler from Bethlehem would have origins "from of old, from ancient times" (literally "from days of eternity"). This isn''t describing a mere human king—it''s describing someone who existed before time began.

How did Jesus end up being born in Bethlehem? His parents lived in Nazareth, about 90 miles away. It took a decree from Caesar Augustus—the most powerful man in the world—ordering a census that required people to return to their ancestral towns. Joseph, being of David''s line, had to go to Bethlehem, David''s city.

Think about the orchestration required: a pagan emperor, knowing nothing of Jewish prophecy, issues an administrative order that moves a pregnant woman to exactly the right location at exactly the right time. Mary and Joseph didn''t choose Bethlehem. Caesar didn''t know about Micah''s prophecy. Yet God''s word, spoken 700 years earlier, was fulfilled precisely.

The religious leaders knew this prophecy well. When the Magi asked Herod where the Messiah would be born, the chief priests and scribes immediately quoted Micah 5:2. They knew where to look—they just didn''t go look.'
WHERE plan_id = (SELECT id FROM public.reading_plans WHERE slug = 'messianic-prophecies-fulfilled') 
