-- Day 3: From the Line of David
UPDATE public.reading_plan_days 
SET context = 'God made a covenant with King David around 1000 BC, promising that his throne would be established forever. The prophet Jeremiah, writing about 400 years later during Judah''s darkest days, reaffirmed this promise: God would raise up a "righteous Branch" from David''s line who would reign wisely and be called "The LORD Our Righteousness."

By the time Jesus was born, the Davidic monarchy had been defunct for nearly 600 years. The Jews were under Roman occupation. No descendant of David sat on any throne. The royal line seemed to have reached a dead end.

Yet both Matthew and Luke carefully document Jesus'' genealogy, tracing His lineage back to David. Matthew traces Joseph''s line (Jesus'' legal ancestry), while Luke likely traces Mary''s line (His biological ancestry through His mother). Both converge on David.

This matters because God''s promises are specific. The Messiah couldn''t come from just any Jewish family—He had to come from David''s house. The genealogies, which modern readers often skip, were essential proof to first-century Jews that Jesus had the right credentials.

Jeremiah''s title for the Messiah—"The LORD Our Righteousness"—is remarkable. In Hebrew, it''s "Yahweh Tsidkenu." Jeremiah is saying the coming King won''t just be righteous; He will BE Yahweh (God''s personal name) who becomes our righteousness. This is exactly what Paul later explains: Christ "has become for us wisdom from God—that is, our righteousness, holiness and redemption" (1 Corinthians 1:30).

The Branch from David''s stump didn''t just restore an earthly kingdom—He established an eternal one.'
WHERE plan_id = (SELECT id FROM public.reading_plans WHERE slug = 'messianic-prophecies-fulfilled') 
