-- Day 4: Called Out of Egypt
UPDATE public.reading_plan_days 
SET context = 'This prophecy demonstrates one of the most fascinating aspects of biblical interpretation: how events in Israel''s history foreshadow (or "typify") events in Jesus'' life.

Hosea 11:1 originally referred to the Exodus—God calling the nation of Israel, His "son," out of Egypt. Yet Matthew, inspired by the Holy Spirit, sees a deeper fulfillment when Joseph takes Mary and the infant Jesus to Egypt to escape Herod''s massacre, and later returns after Herod''s death.

How can a historical statement about Israel also be a prophecy about Jesus? Because Jesus is the true Israel—He embodies and fulfills everything Israel was meant to be. Where Israel failed, Jesus succeeded. Israel was God''s son who was often unfaithful; Jesus is God''s Son who was perfectly faithful.

This pattern repeats throughout Scripture: Israel spent 40 years in the wilderness being tested; Jesus spent 40 days in the wilderness being tested. Israel crossed through the Red Sea; Jesus was baptized in the Jordan. Israel received the Law at Sinai; Jesus delivered the Sermon on the Mount.

Jesus relives Israel''s story and gets it right. He is the faithful Son, the true Vine, the genuine Israel. What seemed like a desperate flight to Egypt to escape a murderous king was actually the fulfillment of prophetic pattern—God''s Son being called out of Egypt to bring salvation not just to one nation, but to all nations.

The early church father Irenaeus called this "recapitulation"—Jesus recapitulating (summarizing and completing) all of human and Israelite history in Himself.'
