-- Day 5: Preceded by a Messenger
UPDATE public.reading_plan_days 
SET context = 'Both Malachi (the last Old Testament prophet, around 430 BC) and Isaiah (about 700 BC) predicted that a messenger would prepare the way for the Lord''s coming. Isaiah describes "a voice calling in the wilderness: Prepare the way for the LORD."

For 400 years after Malachi, no prophetic voice was heard in Israel. This "silent period" made the appearance of John the Baptist all the more dramatic. Suddenly, a wild man emerges from the wilderness wearing camel''s hair and eating locusts, proclaiming that the kingdom of heaven is near.

John himself explicitly identified his role using Isaiah''s words: "I am the voice of one calling in the wilderness, ''Make straight the way for the Lord.''" He understood his mission wasn''t to draw attention to himself but to prepare people for someone greater.

Malachi''s prophecy is even more striking: "I will send my messenger, who will prepare the way before me. Then suddenly the Lord you are seeking will come to his temple." Notice: the messenger prepares the way before "me"—God speaking. Then "the Lord" comes to His temple. The messenger prepares the way for God Himself to arrive.

John prepared the way for Jesus. If the prophecy is accurate, that means Jesus is the Lord—Yahweh in human flesh—coming to His temple. This is exactly what happened when Jesus cleansed the temple, declaring it "my Father''s house."

Jesus confirmed John''s identity: "This is the one about whom it is written: ''I will send my messenger ahead of you, who will prepare your way before you.''" The last Old Testament prophecy found its fulfillment in the first New Testament prophet.'
