-- Day 6: Ministry in Galilee
UPDATE public.reading_plan_days 
SET context = 'Isaiah prophesied that the lands of Zebulun and Naphtali—the region of Galilee—would be honored after initially being humbled. This area, in northern Israel, was the first to fall to Assyrian conquest in 732 BC. It was considered a backwater, a place of mixed populations and questionable religious purity. "Can anything good come from Nazareth?" was a common sentiment.

Yet Isaiah declared that this despised region would see "a great light." The people walking in darkness would experience dawn.

Jesus grew up in Nazareth of Galilee. He launched His public ministry not in Jerusalem (the religious center) or Judea (the "pure" Jewish heartland) but in Galilee. He called His first disciples—fishermen from Galilee. He performed His first miracle in Cana of Galilee. He delivered many of His most famous teachings around the Sea of Galilee.

Matthew explicitly connects this to Isaiah''s prophecy: by ministering in Galilee, Jesus was fulfilling the promise that light would dawn on those in darkness.

There''s a profound theological point here. God doesn''t start with the elite, the powerful, or the religiously respectable. He begins in obscure Bethlehem, grows up in despised Nazareth, and ministers in "Galilee of the Gentiles." The last become first. The humble are exalted. The places everyone overlooks become the stage for God''s greatest work.

The religious leaders in Jerusalem largely rejected Jesus. But in Galilee—among fishermen, tax collectors, and ordinary people—the light shone and was received.'
WHERE plan_id = (SELECT id FROM public.reading_plans WHERE slug = 'messianic-prophecies-fulfilled') 
