-- Day 7: Healing and Miracles
UPDATE public.reading_plan_days 
SET context = 'Isaiah 35 paints a beautiful picture of what the Messianic age would look like: "Then will the eyes of the blind be opened and the ears of the deaf unstopped. Then will the lame leap like a deer, and the mute tongue shout for joy."

When John the Baptist, sitting in Herod''s prison, sent messengers to ask Jesus if He was truly "the one who is to come," Jesus didn''t give a theological lecture. He pointed to the evidence: "Go back and report to John what you hear and see: The blind receive sight, the lame walk, those who have leprosy are cleansed, the deaf hear, the dead are raised, and the good news is proclaimed to the poor."

Jesus was essentially saying, "Look at Isaiah 35. It''s happening. Draw your own conclusion."

The miracles weren''t random displays of power. They were prophetic signs—credentials proving Jesus was the promised Messiah. Each healing was a preview of the complete restoration God will bring when Christ returns. Every blind eye opened pointed to a coming day when all blindness—physical and spiritual—will be healed. Every lame person who walked anticipated a new creation where nothing will be broken.

The religious leaders demanded signs, but they ignored the signs right in front of them. People who had been blind from birth were seeing. People who hadn''t walked in decades were leaping. The dead were being raised. Isaiah''s prophecy was being fulfilled in their streets, and they missed it because Jesus didn''t fit their expectations.

The question John asked from prison is the same question everyone must answer: Is Jesus the One, or should we expect another? His miracles provide the answer.'
WHERE plan_id = (SELECT id FROM public.reading_plans WHERE slug = 'messianic-prophecies-fulfilled') 
