-- Day 8: Speaking in Parables
UPDATE public.reading_plan_days 
SET context = 'Psalm 78 opens with a declaration that the psalmist will speak in parables and "utter hidden things, things from of old." Matthew sees this pattern fulfilled in Jesus'' teaching ministry, where parables became His primary method of public instruction.

A parable is a story drawn from everyday life that reveals spiritual truth. Jesus told stories about farmers and seeds, lost sheep and coins, fathers and sons, kings and servants. The images were familiar; the meanings were profound.

But why speak in parables? Wouldn''t straightforward teaching be clearer? Jesus explained to His disciples that parables served a dual purpose: to reveal truth to those with receptive hearts and to conceal it from those who had already rejected Him. "The knowledge of the secrets of the kingdom of heaven has been given to you, but not to them."

This seems harsh until you understand the context. The religious leaders had already decided to destroy Jesus. They attributed His miracles to Satan. They had hardened their hearts against the truth. Speaking plainly to them would only increase their condemnation. The parables gave them what they wanted—an excuse to dismiss Him—while preserving deeper truth for those genuinely seeking.

Jesus'' parables fulfilled another prophecy from Isaiah 6: the people would be "ever hearing but never understanding; ever seeing but never perceiving." Spiritual blindness isn''t just about not having information—it''s about refusing to receive truth that''s clearly presented.

The same parables that confounded the proud enlightened the humble. The message was the same; the hearts were different.'
WHERE plan_id = (SELECT id FROM public.reading_plans WHERE slug = 'messianic-prophecies-fulfilled') 
