-- Day 9: Entering Jerusalem on a Donkey
UPDATE public.reading_plan_days 
SET context = 'Zechariah, prophesying around 520 BC, described the Messiah''s entrance into Jerusalem in vivid detail: "See, your king comes to you, righteous and victorious, lowly and riding on a donkey, on a colt, the foal of a donkey."

This was not how kings typically arrived. Conquering kings rode war horses. They came with armies and chariots. But Zechariah''s king comes "lowly" (or "humble"), riding a donkey—an animal of peace.

Jesus orchestrated His entrance to fulfill this prophecy precisely. He sent disciples to find a donkey and its colt, telling them exactly where to look and what to say. The owners let the animals go, just as Jesus predicted. He rode into Jerusalem while crowds spread their cloaks and palm branches on the road, shouting "Hosanna to the Son of David!"

The "Triumphal Entry" happened on what we call Palm Sunday, exactly as Zechariah foretold. But the triumph was ironic. Within a week, the same crowds would cry "Crucify Him!" The king came to His capital, and His capital rejected Him.

Yet even in this, prophecy was fulfilled. Jesus wept over Jerusalem, saying, "If you, even you, had only known on this day what would bring you peace—but now it is hidden from your eyes." The city didn''t recognize the day of its "visitation" (Luke 19:44).

The donkey matters. Jesus came the first time as a humble servant, offering peace. When He returns, Revelation shows Him on a white horse, coming as conquering King. The first time fulfilled Zechariah 9:9—humble and riding a donkey. The second time will fulfill the rest of the prophecy—bringing justice to the nations.'
WHERE plan_id = (SELECT id FROM public.reading_plans WHERE slug = 'messianic-prophecies-fulfilled') 
