-- Day 10: Betrayed by a Friend
UPDATE public.reading_plan_days 
SET context = 'Psalm 41, written by David about 1000 BC, contains a haunting line: "Even my close friend, someone I trusted, one who shared my bread, has turned against me." David experienced betrayal by his advisor Ahithophel, who joined Absalom''s rebellion. But the psalm finds its ultimate fulfillment in Jesus and Judas.

Jesus quoted this exact verse at the Last Supper, applying it to His coming betrayal. "I am not referring to all of you; I know those I have chosen. But this is to fulfill this passage of Scripture: ''He who shared my bread has turned against me.''"

The intimacy of the betrayal makes it worse. Judas wasn''t a distant enemy. He was one of the Twelve, hand-picked by Jesus, entrusted with the group''s money, present for three years of miracles and teaching. He reclined at the same table, dipped bread in the same dish.

John''s Gospel provides haunting details. Jesus dipped bread and gave it to Judas, a gesture of honor and friendship. Then "Satan entered into him." Jesus said, "What you are about to do, do quickly." Judas went out, and John adds the chilling observation: "And it was night."

Why did Judas betray Jesus? The Gospels don''t fully explain. Greed played a role—he stole from the money bag. Disillusionment perhaps—Jesus wasn''t the political Messiah Judas wanted. Whatever the human motivations, the betrayal was prophesied a millennium earlier.

Even in this darkest moment, Jesus remained in control. He knew who would betray Him, when it would happen, and how it would unfold. The betrayal didn''t catch God off guard—it fulfilled His word.'
WHERE plan_id = (SELECT id FROM public.reading_plans WHERE slug = 'messianic-prophecies-fulfilled') 
