-- Day 11: Sold for Thirty Pieces of Silver
UPDATE public.reading_plan_days 
SET context = 'Zechariah 11 contains one of the most specific and remarkable prophecies about the Messiah''s betrayal. The prophet, acting out a symbolic drama, asks for his wages after serving as a shepherd. He''s paid thirty pieces of silver—the price of a slave (Exodus 21:32). God tells him to "throw it to the potter"—this "handsome price at which they valued me."

The sarcasm is biting. Thirty silver coins was an insultingly low amount—the compensation owed if your ox gored someone''s slave. That''s how much they valued God''s shepherd.

Five hundred years later, Judas approached the chief priests asking, "What are you willing to give me if I deliver him over to you?" They counted out thirty pieces of silver—exactly the amount Zechariah prophesied.

The fulfillment continues. When Judas saw that Jesus was condemned, he was seized with remorse. He threw the silver pieces into the temple and went and hanged himself. The priests, deciding the money was tainted, used it to buy the potter''s field as a burial place for foreigners.

Matthew explicitly notes this fulfilled "what was spoken by Jeremiah the prophet" (attributing it to Jeremiah because that prophetic book came first in the Hebrew ordering, though the quote is from Zechariah). Every detail matches: thirty pieces of silver, thrown in the temple, used to buy a potter''s field.

No human could have arranged these details. Judas didn''t know about Zechariah 11. The priests weren''t trying to fulfill prophecy. Yet their freely-made decisions—the exact price, throwing the money into the temple, buying a potter''s field—matched a 500-year-old prophecy precisely.'
WHERE plan_id = (SELECT id FROM public.reading_plans WHERE slug = 'messianic-prophecies-fulfilled') 
AND day_number = 11;

-- Day 12: Silent Before Accusers
UPDATE public.reading_plan_days 
SET context = 'Isaiah 53, often called the "Suffering Servant" passage, describes someone who "was oppressed and afflicted, yet he did not open his mouth; he was led like a lamb to the slaughter, and as a sheep before its shearers is silent, so he did not open his mouth."

This is remarkable because silence before accusers was not the norm. Jewish and Roman legal proceedings expected the accused to defend themselves. Remaining silent was seen as accepting guilt. Any innocent person would naturally protest, explain, argue.

Yet Jesus, standing before the Sanhedrin, Pilate, and Herod, remained largely silent. "When he was accused by the chief priests and the elders, he gave no answer. Then Pilate asked him, ''Don''t you hear the testimony they are bringing against you?'' But Jesus made no reply, not even to a single charge—to the great amazement of the governor."

Pilate was amazed because this never happened. Prisoners begged, argued, made excuses. Jesus stood silent.

Why? Because He was not a victim being railroaded—He was a sacrifice being offered. Lambs don''t argue with the priest. They are led silently to the altar. Jesus understood His mission: "No one takes my life from me, but I lay it down of my own accord."

His silence also fulfilled another dimension of Isaiah''s prophecy. The Servant was "assigned a grave with the wicked" though "he had done no violence, nor was any deceit in his mouth." Jesus didn''t protest His innocence because He was willingly taking the place of the guilty. He wasn''t silent from weakness but from determined purpose.'
WHERE plan_id = (SELECT id FROM public.reading_plans WHERE slug = 'messianic-prophecies-fulfilled') 
