-- Day 13: Beaten and Spat Upon
UPDATE public.reading_plan_days 
SET context = 'Isaiah 50:6 describes the Servant''s suffering in visceral terms: "I offered my back to those who beat me, my cheeks to those who pulled out my beard; I did not hide my face from mocking and spitting."

In the ancient Near East, pulling someone''s beard and spitting in their face were extreme insults—signs of utter contempt and rejection. Combined with beating, this describes systematic humiliation designed to break a person''s spirit.

The Gospel accounts record exactly these abuses. During Jesus'' trial before the Sanhedrin, "they spit in his face and struck him with their fists. Others slapped him." Before Pilate, the Roman soldiers "stripped him and put a scarlet robe on him, and then twisted together a crown of thorns and set it on his head... They spit on him, and took the staff and struck him on the head again and again."

The mockery was calculated cruelty. They dressed Him in royal purple, gave Him a reed as a scepter, and bowed in mock worship: "Hail, king of the Jews!" They were ridiculing His claim to kingship, not knowing they were actually worshiping the true King of the universe.

Notice Isaiah''s wording: "I offered my back... I did not hide my face." This isn''t passive victimization—it''s voluntary submission. The Servant willingly endured the abuse. Jesus could have called twelve legions of angels. He could have struck His tormentors blind or dead. Instead, He "offered" Himself to their brutality.

Peter later wrote: "When they hurled their insults at him, he did not retaliate; when he suffered, he made no threats. Instead, he entrusted himself to him who judges justly" (1 Peter 2:23).'
