-- Day 14: Crucified with Criminals
UPDATE public.reading_plan_days 
SET context = 'Isaiah 53:12 prophesied that the Servant would be "numbered with the transgressors." Though completely innocent, He would be counted as a criminal, executed alongside criminals.

Luke records: "Two other men, both criminals, were led out with him to be executed. When they came to the place called the Skull, they crucified him there, along with the criminals—one on his right, the other on his left."

Jesus, the only truly innocent person who ever lived, died between two guilty men. He wasn''t given a special execution befitting His innocence—He was treated as just another criminal, His cross indistinguishable from the others except for Pilate''s sign.

But the story doesn''t end with the humiliation. One of those criminals, watching Jesus die, had a change of heart. While the other criminal hurled insults, this man rebuked him: "Don''t you fear God, since you are under the same sentence? We are punished justly, for we are getting what our deeds deserve. But this man has done nothing wrong."

Then he said, "Jesus, remember me when you come into your kingdom." And Jesus replied, "Truly I tell you, today you will be with me in paradise."

In His death, Jesus did exactly what He came to do—save sinners. The very criminals He was "numbered with" became the recipients of His grace. One rejected Him; one received Him. The cross between criminals became a place of judgment and salvation.

This is the gospel in miniature: the innocent One takes His place among the guilty, and those who trust Him receive paradise.'
