-- Day 15: Hands and Feet Pierced
UPDATE public.reading_plan_days 
SET context = 'Psalm 22, written by David around 1000 BC, contains a line that has puzzled Jewish interpreters for centuries: "They pierce my hands and my feet." David never experienced this. No form of execution in ancient Israel involved piercing hands and feet.

Yet 1,000 years after David wrote these words, the Romans perfected a method of execution that did exactly this: crucifixion. Iron spikes were driven through the victim''s wrists and feet, pinning them to a wooden cross.

The Jews didn''t practice crucifixion. It was a Roman innovation, considered so shameful that Roman citizens were exempt from it. David couldn''t have known about crucifixion through natural means—it didn''t exist in his world.

After His resurrection, Jesus appeared to His disciples. Thomas, who had missed the first appearance, declared he wouldn''t believe unless he could see and touch the nail marks in Jesus'' hands and the wound in His side. A week later, Jesus appeared again and invited Thomas: "Put your finger here; see my hands. Reach out your hand and put it into my side. Stop doubting and believe."

Thomas''s response? "My Lord and my God!" The pierced hands became proof of identity and grounds for worship.

The wounds remained even in Jesus'' glorified resurrection body. When He returns, Revelation says, people will "look on the one they have pierced" (quoting Zechariah 12:10). Throughout eternity, the Lamb will bear the marks of His sacrifice. The pierced hands that David prophesied a millennium before crucifixion existed will be visible forever.'
WHERE plan_id = (SELECT id FROM public.reading_plans WHERE slug = 'messianic-prophecies-fulfilled') 
