-- Day 16: Mocked and Scorned
UPDATE public.reading_plan_days 
SET context = 'Psalm 22 contains perhaps the most detailed prophecy of crucifixion in the Old Testament, written 1,000 years before the event. The psalmist describes being surrounded by enemies who mock him with specific words: "He trusts in the LORD; let the LORD rescue him. Let him deliver him, since he delights in him."

Matthew records that while Jesus hung on the cross, "Those who passed by hurled insults at him, shaking their heads... In the same way the chief priests, the teachers of the law and the elders mocked him. ''He saved others,'' they said, ''but he can''t save himself!... He trusts in God. Let God rescue him now if he wants him.''"

The mockers at the cross didn''t know they were quoting Psalm 22. They thought they were making up their own insults. But their spontaneous words of derision matched David''s prophecy verbatim.

There''s deep irony here. They mocked Jesus for trusting God, not knowing He was doing exactly that—trusting the Father''s plan of salvation. They taunted that He "saved others but can''t save himself," not understanding that He could save Himself but chose not to, because saving Himself would mean not saving others.

Psalm 22 begins with the words Jesus cried from the cross: "My God, my God, why have you forsaken me?" Any Jewish hearer would recognize this as the opening line of the psalm. By quoting it, Jesus was pointing them to the entire psalm—including its triumphant ending, where God does answer, and "future generations will be told about the Lord."

The mockers quoted prophecy without knowing it. Jesus quoted it so they could know it.'
