-- Day 17: Given Gall and Vinegar
UPDATE public.reading_plan_days 
SET context = 'Psalm 69, another psalm of David, describes intense suffering that finds ultimate fulfillment in Christ: "They put gall in my food and gave me vinegar for my thirst."

Gall was a bitter, poisonous substance. Vinegar (or sour wine) was the cheap drink of common people and soldiers. Both represent cruelty to someone in desperate need—offering bitterness instead of comfort.

The Gospels record two different drinks offered to Jesus at the cross. First, before crucifixion, they offered Him "wine mixed with gall" (Matthew 27:34) or "wine mixed with myrrh" (Mark 15:23). This was actually a mild mercy—a narcotic mixture intended to dull the pain. Jesus tasted it but refused to drink. He would face the full weight of suffering with unclouded mind.

Later, near the end, Jesus said "I am thirsty." A sponge was soaked in sour wine and lifted to His lips. After receiving it, Jesus declared "It is finished" and died.

The physical thirst pointed to a deeper reality. Jesus, who offered living water to the woman at the well, experienced terrible thirst on the cross. The One who said "whoever drinks the water I give them will never thirst" was Himself dying of thirst.

John notes that Jesus said "I am thirsty" specifically "so that Scripture would be fulfilled." Even in His agony, Jesus was aware of prophetic fulfillment. He wasn''t merely a victim of circumstances—He was consciously completing what had been written about Him.

The bitter drink fulfilled Psalm 69. The vinegar fulfilled it. Everything had been foretold.'
WHERE plan_id = (SELECT id FROM public.reading_plans WHERE slug = 'messianic-prophecies-fulfilled') 
