-- Day 18: Bones Not Broken
UPDATE public.reading_plan_days 
SET context = 'Psalm 34:20 declares of the righteous sufferer: "He protects all his bones, not one of them will be broken." This finds its fulfillment in an unusual detail of Jesus'' crucifixion.

Crucifixion was designed to kill slowly through exhaustion, dehydration, and eventually asphyxiation. Victims could linger for days. To hasten death—especially before the Sabbath—executioners would break the victim''s legs (called "crurifragium"). Unable to push up to breathe, death would come quickly.

John records: "Now it was the day of Preparation, and the next day was to be a special Sabbath. Because the Jewish leaders did not want the bodies left on the crosses during the Sabbath, they asked Pilate to have the legs broken and the bodies taken down."

The soldiers broke the legs of the two criminals crucified with Jesus. But when they came to Jesus, He was already dead. So "they did not break his legs." Instead, to confirm death, a soldier pierced His side with a spear, bringing "a sudden flow of blood and water."

John emphasizes: "The man who saw it has given testimony, and his testimony is true. He knows that he tells the truth, and he testifies so that you also may believe. These things happened so that the scripture would be fulfilled: ''Not one of his bones will be broken.''"

This connects to another prophetic thread: the Passover lamb. Exodus 12:46 required that no bone of the Passover lamb be broken. Jesus is "the Lamb of God who takes away the sin of the world" (John 1:29). His bones remained intact, just like the Passover lambs of old.

Every detail was orchestrated—even the timing of His death and the soldiers'' actions.'
WHERE plan_id = (SELECT id FROM public.reading_plans WHERE slug = 'messianic-prophecies-fulfilled') 
AND day_number = 18;

-- Day 19: Side Pierced
UPDATE public.reading_plan_days 
SET context = 'Zechariah 12:10 contains a stunning prophecy: "They will look on me, the one they have pierced, and they will mourn for him as one mourns for an only child."

Notice who is speaking: God says "they will look on ME, the one they have pierced." God is describing Himself being pierced. How can the eternal, spiritual God be pierced?

The answer is the incarnation. God the Son took on human flesh and was pierced on a Roman cross. John, standing at the foot of the cross, witnessed the fulfillment: "One of the soldiers pierced Jesus'' side with a spear, bringing a sudden flow of blood and water... these things happened so that the scripture would be fulfilled... ''They will look on the one they have pierced.''"

John changed "me" to "the one"—not contradicting Zechariah but clarifying that Jesus, the one pierced, is the Lord of Zechariah''s prophecy.

The blood and water have theological significance. Some see them representing the two sacraments: communion (blood) and baptism (water). Others see them proving real death—the separation of blood cells and serum that occurs after death. Still others see them representing the two key elements of salvation: blood for forgiveness, water for cleansing.

Zechariah continues: mourning will follow the piercing. On the Day of Pentecost, when Peter preached that Israel had crucified their Messiah, "they were cut to the heart" and 3,000 repented and were baptized. The mourning had begun.

The full mourning awaits Christ''s return, when "every eye will see him, even those who pierced him; and all peoples on earth will mourn because of him" (Revelation 1:7).'
WHERE plan_id = (SELECT id FROM public.reading_plans WHERE slug = 'messianic-prophecies-fulfilled') 
AND day_number = 19;

-- Day 20: Buried in a Rich Man's Tomb
UPDATE public.reading_plan_days 
SET context = 'Isaiah 53:9 contains a seemingly contradictory prophecy: "He was assigned a grave with the wicked, and with the rich in his death, though he had done no violence, nor was any deceit in his mouth."

How can someone be buried with both the wicked AND the rich? Crucified criminals were typically thrown into common graves or left for scavengers. Jesus was "assigned" (destined for) such a grave—He was executed as a criminal between criminals.

But something unexpected happened. Joseph of Arimathea, described by Matthew as "a rich man" and by Mark as "a prominent member of the Council," boldly asked Pilate for Jesus'' body. He took the body, wrapped it in clean linen, and "placed it in his own new tomb that he had cut out of the rock."

Jesus died among the wicked (the two criminals) but was buried among the rich (in Joseph''s expensive tomb). Both parts of Isaiah''s prophecy were fulfilled.

Joseph''s actions were costly. As a member of the Sanhedrin (the Jewish ruling council), publicly honoring Jesus would end his political career and invite persecution. Handling a dead body made him ceremonially unclean for Passover. The expensive tomb, meant for himself, was given to a convicted criminal.

Yet Isaiah already knew. Seven centuries before Joseph was born, the prophet recorded that a rich man would provide the Messiah''s grave.

The new tomb was also significant. No body had ever been placed in it. When Jesus rose, no one could claim the wrong body had emerged or that His bones had been confused with another''s. The tomb''s newness testified to the uniqueness of His resurrection.'
WHERE plan_id = (SELECT id FROM public.reading_plans WHERE slug = 'messianic-prophecies-fulfilled') 
AND day_number = 20;

-- Day 21: Risen from the Dead
UPDATE public.reading_plan_days 
SET context = 'All the prophecies we''ve studied would mean nothing if Jesus had stayed dead. A dead Messiah is a failed Messiah. But Psalm 16, written by David 1,000 years before Christ, contains a remarkable statement: "You will not abandon me to the realm of the dead, nor will you let your faithful one see decay."

David died and was buried. His tomb was known and visited in Peter''s day. David''s body did see decay. So what did David mean?

Peter, preaching on the Day of Pentecost, explains: "Fellow Israelites, I can tell you confidently that the patriarch David died and was buried, and his tomb is here to this day. But he was a prophet and knew that God had promised him on oath that he would place one of his descendants on his throne. Seeing what was to come, he spoke of the resurrection of the Messiah, that he was not abandoned to the realm of the dead, nor did his body see decay."

David was prophesying about his greater descendant—the Messiah whose body would not decay because He would rise from the dead.

Paul makes the same point in Acts 13: "When David had served God''s purpose in his own generation, he fell asleep; he was buried with his ancestors and his body decayed. But the one whom God raised from the dead did not see decay."

The resurrection is the vindication of everything Jesus claimed. It proves He is who He said He was. It confirms that His sacrifice was accepted. It guarantees that everyone who trusts in Him will also rise.

Over 300 prophecies fulfilled. A virgin birth, a Bethlehem birthplace, a ministry in Galilee, betrayal for thirty silver coins, silence before accusers, pierced hands and feet, bones unbroken, burial in a rich man''s tomb, and resurrection from the dead.

The mathematical probability of one person fulfilling just eight of these prophecies by chance has been calculated at 1 in 10^17 (one hundred quadrillion). Jesus fulfilled over 300.

The evidence is overwhelming: Jesus is the promised Messiah, the Son of God, the Savior of the world.'
WHERE plan_id = (SELECT id FROM public.reading_plans WHERE slug = 'messianic-prophecies-fulfilled') 
AND day_number = 21;
